type="user">jms-00LZ</fr:addr><fr:route>jms-00LZ.xml</fr:route><fr:title
text="Cardinality of the disjoint sum">Cardinality of the disjoint sum</fr:title><fr:taxon>Example</fr:taxon><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>1</fr:month><fr:day>28</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
type="local"
href="jonmsterling.xml"
addr="jonmsterling"
title="Jon Sterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author><fr:contributor><fr:link
type="local"
href="marcelofiore.xml"
addr="marcelofiore"
title="Marcelo Fiore">Marcelo Fiore</fr:link></fr:contributor></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>For all <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[m,n\in \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex>, we have <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left  [m\right  ]\mathclose {}}+{\mathopen {}\left  [n\right  ]\mathclose {}} \cong  {\mathopen {}\left  [m+n\right  ]\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree
toc="false"
numbered="true"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>1843</fr:anchor><fr:addr
type="machine">#391</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-391.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>1</fr:month><fr:day>28</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
type="local"
href="jonmsterling.xml"
addr="jonmsterling"
title="Jon Sterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
 <fr:p>We can think of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left  [m\right  ]\mathclose {}}+{\mathopen {}\left  [n\right  ]\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> as the set of coordinates into two strips of cells, the first of which has <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[m]]></fr:tex> cells and the second of which has <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex> cells. Conversely, we can think of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left  [m+n\right  ]\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> as the set of coordinates a single strip of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[m+n]]></fr:tex> cells. A function <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[I\colon {\mathopen {}\left  [m\right  ]\mathclose {}}+{\mathopen {}\left  [n\right  ]\mathclose {}}\to  {\mathopen {}\left  [m+n\right  ]\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> could then be thought of as witnessing a method to lay out the two strips in serial; we will define such a function and show that it is a bijection.</fr:p>

 <fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[   \begin {aligned}    I &\colon {\mathopen {}\left  [m\right  ]\mathclose {}}+{\mathopen {}\left  [n\right  ]\mathclose {}} \to  {\mathopen {}\left  [m+n\right  ]\mathclose {}}\\    I{\mathopen {}\left (0,i<m\right )\mathclose {}} &= i\\    I{\mathopen {}\left (1,j<n\right )\mathclose {}} &= m+j   \end {aligned}  ]]></fr:tex>

 <fr:p>The function <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[I]]></fr:tex> places a cell from the first strip sequentially after the first <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[m]]></fr:tex> cells of the serialised strip. The inverse can be defined as follows:</fr:p>

 <fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[   I{\mathopen {}\left (k\right )\mathclose {}} =   \begin {cases}    {\mathopen {}\left (0,k\right )\mathclose {}} &\text {when } k < m\\    {\mathopen {}\left (1,k-m\right )\mathclose {}} &\text {when } k \geq  m   \end {cases}  ]]></fr:tex>
</fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>
 
</fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
