type="local"
href="marcelofiore.xml"
addr="marcelofiore"
title="Marcelo Fiore">Marcelo Fiore</fr:link></fr:contributor></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>For <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00LX.xml"
addr="jms-00LX"
title="Finite set">finite sets</fr:link> <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex>, we can describe number of <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00MO.xml"
addr="jms-00MO"
title="Injection">injections</fr:link> from <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex> as follows:</fr:p><fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[  \mathord {\#}{\mathrm {Inj}{\mathopen {}\left (A,B\right )\mathclose {}}} =  \begin {cases}   {\mathord {\#}{B}\choose \mathord {\#}{A}}\cdot  {\mathopen {}\left (\mathord {\#}{A}\right )\mathclose {}}! &\text {when } \mathord {\#}{A}\leq  \mathord {\#}{B}   \\   0 &\text {otherwise}  \end {cases} ]]></fr:tex>
 
   
   <fr:tree
toc="false"
numbered="true"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>1945</fr:anchor><fr:addr
type="machine">#378</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-378.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>1</fr:month><fr:day>30</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
type="local"
href="jonmsterling.xml"
addr="jonmsterling"
title="Jon Sterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
 <fr:p>We will argue from a combinatoric perspective.</fr:p>

 <fr:p>An <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00MO.xml"
addr="jms-00MO"
title="Injection">injection</fr:link> <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> from <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex> associates no more than one <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a\in  A]]></fr:tex> to the same <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[b\in  B]]></fr:tex>. Thus if we consider the subset <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[U\subseteq  B]]></fr:tex> spanned by elements of the form <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f{\mathopen {}\left (a\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>, we should then get a <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00KR.xml"
addr="jms-00KR"
title="Bijection">bijection</fr:link> from <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[U]]></fr:tex>as each <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[b\in  U]]></fr:tex> comes from a <fr:em>unique</fr:em> <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a\in  A]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>

 <fr:p>Therefore, choosing an <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00MO.xml"
addr="jms-00MO"
title="Injection">injection</fr:link> amounts to making <fr:em>two</fr:em> independent choices: first we choose a subset of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex> that is in <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00KR.xml"
addr="jms-00KR"
title="Bijection">bijection</fr:link> with <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>, and then we choose a <fr:em>specific</fr:em> <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00KR.xml"
addr="jms-00KR"
title="Bijection">bijection</fr:link> from <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> to that subset. The number of such subsets is precisely <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathord {\#}{B}\choose  \mathord {\#}{A}]]></fr:tex>, and we have already seen in <fr:ref
addr="jms-00KT"
href="jms-00KT.xml"
taxon="Proposition" /> that the number of such bijections is the factorial <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left (\mathord {\#}{A}!\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>

 <fr:p>Of course, if there is no subset of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex> equinumerous with <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>, then there can be no <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00MO.xml"
addr="jms-00MO"
title="Injection">injection</fr:link>.</fr:p>
</fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>
 
</fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
toc="true"
numbered="false"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="true"
expanded="false"
root="false"
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>4998</fr:anchor><fr:addr
type="user">jms-00LW</fr:addr><fr:route>jms-00LW.xml</fr:route><fr:title
text="Finite and infinite sets">Finite and infinite sets</fr:title><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>1</fr:month><fr:day>28</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
type="local"
href="jonmsterling.xml"
addr="jonmsterling"
title="Jon Sterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author><fr:contributor><fr:link
type="local"
href="marcelofiore.xml"
addr="marcelofiore"
title="Marcelo Fiore">Marcelo Fiore</fr:link></fr:contributor></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Now that we have learned about <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00KR.xml"
addr="jms-00KR"
title="Bijection">bijections</fr:link>, we are ready to replace our intuitive/informal understanding of finite sets and finite cardinality with a formal one.</fr:p><fr:tree
toc="true"
numbered="true"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>1831</fr:anchor><fr:addr
type="user">jms-00LX</fr:addr><fr:route>jms-00LX.xml</fr:route><fr:title
text="Finite set">Finite set</fr:title><fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>1</fr:month><fr:day>28</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
type="local"
href="jonmsterling.xml"
addr="jonmsterling"
title="Jon Sterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author><fr:contributor><fr:link
type="local"
href="marcelofiore.xml"
addr="marcelofiore"
title="Marcelo Fiore">Marcelo Fiore</fr:link></fr:contributor></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>A set <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> is said to be <fr:em><fr:strong>finite</fr:strong></fr:em> or have <fr:em><fr:strong>finite cardinality</fr:strong></fr:em> when it is <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00L0.xml"
addr="jms-00L0"
title="Isomorphic sets">isomorphic</fr:link> to a set of the form <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left  [n\right  ]\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> for some <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n\in  \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex>; in this case, we therefore have <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathord {\#}{A}=n]]></fr:tex>. (Recall that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left  [n\right  ]\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> is the standard <html:span
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"
style="white-space: nowrap"><fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex>-element</html:span> set <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left \{i\in \mathbb {N}\,\middle \vert \,0\leq  i < n\right \}\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>.)</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:p>There are many identities that relate set-theoretic operations on <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00LX.xml"
addr="jms-00LX"
title="Finite set">finite sets</fr:link> to arithmetic operations on their cardinalities. We will illustrate a few of them here.</fr:p><fr:tree
toc="true"
numbered="true"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>1834</fr:anchor><fr:addr
type="user">jms-00LY</fr:addr><fr:route>jms-00LY.xml</fr:route><fr:title
text="Cardinality of the cartesian product">Cardinality of the cartesian product</fr:title><fr:taxon>Example</fr:taxon><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>1</fr:month><fr:day>28</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
type="local"
href="jonmsterling.xml"
addr="jonmsterling"
title="Jon Sterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>For all <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[m,n\in \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex>, we have <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left  [m\right  ]\mathclose {}}\times {\mathopen {}\left  [n\right  ]\mathclose {}} \cong  {\mathopen {}\left  [m\cdot  n\right  ]\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p><fr:p>We can prove this from a combinatoric point of view.</fr:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree
toc="false"
numbered="true"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>1836</fr:anchor><fr:addr
type="machine">#392</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-392.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>1</fr:month><fr:day>28</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
type="local"
href="jonmsterling.xml"
addr="jonmsterling"
title="Jon Sterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
 <fr:p>To choose a pair <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left (i,j\right )\mathclose {}}\in {\mathopen {}\left  [m\right  ]\mathclose {}}\times {\mathopen {}\left  [n\right  ]\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>, we first choose an element of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left  [m\right  ]\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> and we second choose an element of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left  [n\right  ]\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>. There are <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[m]]></fr:tex> possibilities for the first choice and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex> possibilities for the second choice; as these choices are independent, we simply have <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[m\cdot  n]]></fr:tex> choices in total.</fr:p>
</fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>
 
<fr:p>We can also prove this isomorphism more formally by means of a specific bijection.</fr:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree
toc="false"
numbered="true"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>1838</fr:anchor><fr:addr
type="machine">#393</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-393.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>1</fr:month><fr:day>28</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
type="local"
href="jonmsterling.xml"
addr="jonmsterling"
title="Jon Sterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
 <fr:p>We can think of the cartesian product <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left  [m\right  ]\mathclose {}}\times {\mathopen {}\left  [n\right  ]\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> as the set of cells in table or matrix with <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[m]]></fr:tex> columns and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex> rows — and then an element <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left (i,j\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> with <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[i\in {\mathopen {}\left  [m\right  ]\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[j\in {\mathopen {}\left  [n\right  ]\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> is the coordinate of a given cell. Naturally, the total number of cells would be <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[m\cdot  n]]></fr:tex>, but we can prove this formally by constructing the function that takes a coordinate <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left (i,j\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> to its absolute index in the counting of cells from left to right and top to bottom:</fr:p>

 <fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[   \begin {aligned}    I &\colon {\mathopen {}\left  [m\right  ]\mathclose {}}\times {\mathopen {}\left  [n\right  ]\mathclose {}}\to  {\mathopen {}\left  [m\cdot  n\right  ]\mathclose {}}\\    I{\mathopen {}\left (i,j\right )\mathclose {}} &= m\cdot  j + i   \end {aligned}  ]]></fr:tex>
</fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>
 
<fr:p>We do need to check that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[I{\mathopen {}\left (i,j\right )\mathclose {}}< m\cdot  n]]></fr:tex> for all <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[i<m]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[j<n]]></fr:tex>. The maximimum value of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[I]]></fr:tex> is naturally <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[I{\mathopen {}\left (m-1,n-1\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>:</fr:p><fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[  \begin {aligned}   I{\mathopen {}\left (m-1,n-1\right )\mathclose {}} &= m\cdot {\mathopen {}\left (n-1\right )\mathclose {}} + {\mathopen {}\left (m-1\right )\mathclose {}}   \\   &=   m\cdot  n - m + m - 1   \\   &=   m\cdot  n - 1   \\   &< m\cdot  n  \end {aligned} ]]></fr:tex><fr:p>The inverse function <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[I^{-1}\colon {\mathopen {}\left  [m\cdot  n\right  ]\mathclose {}}\to {\mathopen {}\left  [m\right  ]\mathclose {}}\times {\mathopen {}\left  [n\right  ]\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> takes <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[i<m\cdot  n]]></fr:tex> to the pair <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left (\operatorname {rem}{\mathopen {}\left (i,m\right )\mathclose {}}, \operatorname {quo}{\mathopen {}\left (i,m\right )\mathclose {}}\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
toc="true"
numbered="true"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>1840</fr:anchor><fr:addr
type="user">jms-00LZ</fr:addr><fr:route>jms-00LZ.xml</fr:route><fr:title
text="Cardinality of the disjoint sum">Cardinality of the disjoint sum</fr:title><fr:taxon>Example</fr:taxon><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>1</fr:month><fr:day>28</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
type="local"
href="jonmsterling.xml"
addr="jonmsterling"
title="Jon Sterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author><fr:contributor><fr:link
type="local"
href="marcelofiore.xml"
addr="marcelofiore"
title="Marcelo Fiore">Marcelo Fiore</fr:link></fr:contributor></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>For all <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[m,n\in \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex>, we have <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left  [m\right  ]\mathclose {}}+{\mathopen {}\left  [n\right  ]\mathclose {}} \cong  {\mathopen {}\left  [m+n\right  ]\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree
toc="false"
numbered="true"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>1843</fr:anchor><fr:addr
type="machine">#391</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-391.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>1</fr:month><fr:day>28</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
type="local"
href="jonmsterling.xml"
addr="jonmsterling"
title="Jon Sterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
 <fr:p>We can think of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left  [m\right  ]\mathclose {}}+{\mathopen {}\left  [n\right  ]\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> as the set of coordinates into two strips of cells, the first of which has <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[m]]></fr:tex> cells and the second of which has <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex> cells. Conversely, we can think of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left  [m+n\right  ]\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> as the set of coordinates a single strip of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[m+n]]></fr:tex> cells. A function <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[I\colon {\mathopen {}\left  [m\right  ]\mathclose {}}+{\mathopen {}\left  [n\right  ]\mathclose {}}\to  {\mathopen {}\left  [m+n\right  ]\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> could then be thought of as witnessing a method to lay out the two strips in serial; we will define such a function and show that it is a bijection.</fr:p>

 <fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[   \begin {aligned}    I &\colon {\mathopen {}\left  [m\right  ]\mathclose {}}+{\mathopen {}\left  [n\right  ]\mathclose {}} \to  {\mathopen {}\left  [m+n\right  ]\mathclose {}}\\    I{\mathopen {}\left (0,i<m\right )\mathclose {}} &= i\\    I{\mathopen {}\left (1,j<n\right )\mathclose {}} &= m+j   \end {aligned}  ]]></fr:tex>

 <fr:p>The function <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[I]]></fr:tex> places a cell from the first strip sequentially after the first <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[m]]></fr:tex> cells of the serialised strip. The inverse can be defined as follows:</fr:p>

 <fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[   I{\mathopen {}\left (k\right )\mathclose {}} =   \begin {cases}    {\mathopen {}\left (0,k\right )\mathclose {}} &\text {when } k < m\\    {\mathopen {}\left (1,k-m\right )\mathclose {}} &\text {when } k \geq  m   \end {cases}  ]]></fr:tex>
</fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>
 
</fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
